2(c)

Standard errors are clustered at the state of birth level.

2(d)

For the results of this study to be internally valid, the identification strategy needs the parallel trend assumption to hold. It requires that in the absence of treatment, the difference between the treatment and control groups is constant over time.

2(e)

The figure above shows that the parallel trends assumption is broadly satisfied.

Answer 3

3(a)

For the intervening cohorts, who had inter-mediate levels of childhood exposure to the campaign, pre-campaign malaria pre-dicts lower income, but with magnitude that diminishes for later birth years. This is also consistent with the childhood-exposure model, insofar as partial exposure to the campaign confers partial benefits to these middling cohorts.
